Here’s what caught our attention on Tuesday: 1. South Africa, you have new ministers This morning, a couple of South African ministers will be changing their Twitter bios, and their responsibility to the nation. Late on Monday evening, President Cyril Ramaphosa appointed ministers to his new cabinet. Some of the key positions include David Mabuza as Deputy President, Nhlanhla Nene as finance minister, Pravin Gordhan as the minister of public enterprises, Bheki Cele as the minister of police and Malusi Gigaba is back at home affairs. Read the full story here. 2. Fuel price adjustment The Automobile Association (AA) of South Africa announced on Monday that fuel prices are expected to drop in March, due to stable exchange rate and lower international fuel prices. The AA said it expects petrol prices to drop by up to 38 cents a litre, diesel by 47 cents and illuminating paraffin by 26 cents. 3. Aveng interim results Construction group Aveng released its results for the six months ended December 31 2017. While revenue increased by 13% to R16.1 billion, Aveng reported a headline loss of R335 million (2016: R391 million) and a net loss of R346 million (2016: R429 million). A headline loss per share decreased to 84.4 cents loss per share (2016: 98.5 cents loss per share). 4. AECI financial results Explosives and chemicals group AECI’s results for the year ended December 31 2017, showed a gain in profits by 18% to R1 579 million and, according to its statement, its highest recorded headline earnings per share, of 959 cents – which is a 17.2% increase from the previous year. 5. Shoprite results Retail group Shoprite’s results for the half-year ended December 31 2017, showed that trading profit increased by 5% to R4.104 billion, and the group declared a dividend of 205 cents, a 13.9% increase compared to the same period in 2016. The group said in a statement that the results were strongly boosted by the SA supermarket operations.